definition.value: A member of the class of guanidines that is agmatine acetylated at the N4-position.
A substance used to destroy fungal pests.
Any furochromene that consists of a furan ring fused with a coumarin. The fusion may occur in different ways in give several isomers.
Compounds containing at least one furan ring.
A member of the class of blasticidins that is blasticidin S in which the side-chain amino group is acetylated.
A phosphatidylcholine where the phosphatidyl acyl groups are specified as tetradecanoyl (myristoyl).
A hexaric acid derivative that is formally obtained from galactaric acid.
An acetate ester obtained by acetylation of the O-14 position of browniine.
A heteroglycan that consists of a backbone of randomly distributed (1->4)-linked mannose and glucose units with (1->6)-linked galactose units attached to mannose units.
Any glycoglycerolipid having galactosyl as the glyco component.
A hexonic acid that has been found to increase in red blood cells of galactosemic patients.
An organic heteropentacyclic compound that is caranine in which the hydroxy group is acetylated.
An oligosaccharide comprised of galactose residues.
A glycosaminyl group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of a galactosamine and, by extension, of a lower oligosaccharide having a galactosamine at the reducing end.
A glycosyl group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of a galactose and, by extension, of a lower oligosaccharide having galactose at the reducing end.
A glycosylglycerol in which the glycosyl residue specified is galactose.
The chloride salt of acetylcholine, and a parasympatomimetic drug.
Any substance produced by linking galacturonic acid to another substance via a glycosidic bond.
A class of hydrolysable tannins obtained by condensation of the carboxy group of gallic acid (and its polymeric derivatives) with the hydroxy groups of a monosaccharide (most commonly glucose).
A class of beta-D-glucose compounds having an unspecified number of O-galloyl groups in undeined positions.
